The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Karnal, Nov. 8 (PTI): A family from Maharashtra, residing here for the last 15 years, has lodged a complaint alleging that they were threatened by two men who barged into their house.           
	Kalpana, the wife of a construction worker, has alleged that they were threatened as they belonged to Maharashtra, police said. It is an isolated threat as no threat has been issued against other families from the state who reside here, an officer said.                  
	 Bangalore (PTI): Tejas, a light combat aircraft, has made its maiden flight by night. It took off from Bangalore and carried out a set of predetermined manoeuvres to demonstrate its night capability, a DRDO release said.                   
	 Raipur (PTI): A suspected Naxalite has been sentenced to two years rigorous imprisonment under the Chhattisgarh Special Public Security Act 2007. He was the first to be convicted under the act.                   
	 Thrissur (PTI): Peta has called for the removal of a controversial billboard near Thrissur in Kerala depicting a chopped squirrel as pieces of fruit. The tagline of the advertisement is Be fruitful. Petas campaign co-ordinator Ashish Verma said the depiction violated provisions of the Wildlife Protection Act.                   
	 Calcutta: A man fell from an autorickshaw and was run over by a truck on NSC Bose Road on the southern fringes of Calcutta. Aniruddha Guha, 32, fell from the three-wheeler when it braked suddenly in Naktala. A truck coming from the opposite direction crushed him. He was taken to MR Bangur Hospital where he was declared dead.                   
	 Jammu (PTI): Ninety-eight rusted grenades were recovered near the International Border in Samba district, a senior police officer said on Saturday. Locals at a construction site spotted the grenades  probably dumped about two and a half years back  in a bag partly buried in sand, the police said.                                                                                                                         
